,"1329":"1329","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Whithibroke, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1250–1347":"1250–1347","1253–1329":"1253–1329","1279–1348":"1279–1348","1224–Male":"1224–Deceased","1228–Female":"1228–Deceased","1228":"1228","1348":"1348","1347":"1347","1279":"1279","1224":"1224","1253":"1253","1250":"1250","1329":"1329","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Whithibroke, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Castells","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English, Irish:  see  Castles  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Castles","meanings":["English: variant of   Castle  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish (Armagh and Meath): in Ireland, this may be the English name, but it may also be an Anglicized form of <b>Ó Caisil</b>; see   Cashell  ."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir George Castells was born in 1250, in Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Henry FitzHugh de Costello, was 27 and his mother, Joane Fourneys, was 23. He had at least 1 daughter with Alice Cheshire. He died in 1347, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 97."},"et":{"1250–1347":"1250–1347","1253–1329":"1253–1329","1279–1348":"1279–1348","1224–Male":"1224–Surnud","1228–Female":"1228–Surnud","1228":"1228","1348":"1348","1347":"1347","1279":"1279","1224":"1224","1253":"1253","1250":"1250","1329":"1329","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Whithibroke, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1250–1347":"1250–1347","1253–1329":"1253–1329","1279–1348":"1279–1348","1224–Male":"1224–Kuollut","1228–Female":"1228–Kuollut","1228":"1228","1348":"1348","1347":"1347","1279":"1279","1224":"1224","1253":"1253","1250":"1250","1329":"1329","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Whithibroke, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1250–1347":"1250–1347","1253–1329":"1253–1329","1279–1348":"1279–1348","1224–Male":"1224–Décédé","1228–Female":"1228–Décédée","1228":"1228","1348":"1348","1347":"1347","1279":"1279","1224":"1224","1253":"1253","1250":"1250","1329":"1329","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Whithibroke, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Sir George Castells est né en 1250, à Warwickshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Henry FitzHugh de Costello, avait 27 ans et sa mère, Joane Fourneys, avait 23